amond; font-size:12pt">Witnesses: </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Mike Penning MP</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">, Minister for Disabled People, </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Dr Bill </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Gunnyeon</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">, Director for Health and Wellbeing, Chief Medical Adviser and Chief Scientist, and </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Jason Feeney</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">, Benefits Director, gave evidence.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Q1 </span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Chair:</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> Can I welcome you to your first appearance before this Committee, Minister?  It is almost three months since you took up your position.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Mike Penning</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">: That long?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Chair:</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> Hopefully, it </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">has been </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">enough time to get to grips with your brief.  I wonder if you could introduce your team for the record, please.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Jason Feeney</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">: I am Jason Feeney.  I am the Benefits Director at </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">D</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">epartment for </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">ork and </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">ensions (DWP)</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">, and the S</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">enior </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">esponsible </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">O</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">wner (SRO)</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> for </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">Personal Independence Payment (</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">PIP</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Dr </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Gunnyeon</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">: Bill </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">Gunnyeon</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">, Chief Medical Adviser and Director of Health and Wellbeing, DWP.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Q2 </span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Chair:</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> And you</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">, Minister</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">.  Well, as I say, it is almost three months since you took up the post, so I wonder if you could just very briefly</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">—</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">because we do have a lot of detailed questions</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">—explain which parts of your new job you have found the most challenging.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Mike Penning</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">: May I firstly explain to the Committee that it is a brand new portfolio that the Prime Minister has asked me to take on?  It is a Minister of State portfolio for disabled people, but like any portfolio in government, it actually has myriad other responsibilities as well.  I appreciate you did say “briefly”, Madam Chair, but it is rather a long list.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Q3 </span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Chair:</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> We have got the list in front of us, so we understand.  I have got a question about the overlap with the Employment Minister.  My question was about “challenging”: what surprised you?  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Mike Penning</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">: The biggest thing is that it is such a huge portfolio, and a very important portfolio, which is overarching across government.  It is not just within the DWP.  The Prime Minister has specifically asked me to be responsible for the disability portfolio across government to bring government together in a more collegiate way, and I have responsibility to go into the different departments and ask those relevant questions and do those relevant things.  At the same time, there is also the responsibility that goes across government to do with the </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">Paralympic</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> legacy.  It is obviously very important that we build on the legacy from the Paralympics and the Olympics.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Q4 </span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Chair:</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> I understand that you are working on a DWP disability strategy.  What are going to be the priorities for that strategy, and is that going to include all this cross-cutting government stuff that you just described?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Mike Penning</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">: Yes, it will be.  When we publish it, it will be very much across government.  The key to this is opportunity.  One of the conscious things that I have been looking at very carefully is making sure that we give everybody an opportunity, and that they do not feel trapped within the welfare system, and we must make sure that, at the same time, other </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">D</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">epartments step up to the plate </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">by</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> actually working together.  That is very much my portfolio, and I think one of the reasons why the Prime Minister made it a Minister of State role was to give me, if you wish, the clout to go out there and make that sort of thing happen.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Q5 </span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Chair:</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> Is there anything in particular that strikes you as being top of that list of priorities?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Mike Penning</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">: PIP and WCA, which I know the Committee want to talk about this morning, are very challenging.  There is no point hiding away from that, but at the same time, I think it is absolutely right that the reforms that are coming through are done correctly, with the right quality, and at the same time giv</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> people the information they need.  It is a challenge; there is no argument about that.  I accept that.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Q6 </span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Chair:</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> There is some confusion amongst us, certainly, about who is responsible for what with regard to WCA and ESA.  It seems to be shared between you and the Minister for Employment.  Is there a nice, handy definition as to which is your part and which is her part?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Mike Penning</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">: Yes.  I have WCA, and she has the rest.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Q7 </span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Chair:</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> So you are responsible for the medical assessment side of things?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Mike Penning</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">: Yes.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Q8 </span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Chair:</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> What about ESA and how it is dealt with through Jobcentre Plus?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Mike Penning</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">: That is very much hers.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Q9 </span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Chair:</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> That is the other side of it.  So, you are responsible for it up until a decision is made by a decision-maker, and then it goes on to her.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Mike Penning</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">: Yes.  Of course, we are working very closely together, and we have had several discussions as to making sure how my side of that fits firmly into her side, but the Jobcentre Plus side clearly sits with the Employment Minister.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Q10 </span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Chair:</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> What about the mandatory reconsideration of appeals?  Where does that sit?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Mike Penning</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">: That part still sits with me, as I understand it.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Q11 </span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Chair:</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> So, </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">until </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">there is a final decision?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Mike Penning</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">: It is the Justice </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">Department </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">that actually has the final decision, obviously, because of the tribunals, but the process, if you wish, sits with us.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Q12 </span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Chair:</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> So, the wh</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">le process up to when somebody is in ESA payment; th</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">en it</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> goes to the other Minister.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Mike Penning</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">: If I am wrong at any time, pick me up.  Three months in, I am still learning a lot.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Chair:</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> I think that is clear.  Thank you very much.  There have obviously been two big decisions that you have taken, Minister.  I think the first one landed on your desk the first week, and it was about the Independent Living Fund and the court case.  </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">Glenda has some </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">questions on that</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Q13 </span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Glenda Jackson:</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> On the Court of Appeal decision on the closure on the Independent Living Fund, have you decided how you are going to respond?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Mike Penning</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">: No, I have not</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">; </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">I will be the decision Minister for that</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">, but </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">I have not received a submission from my officials.  I understand that the court ruling was very much that the Minister had not been given enough written advice around the Equality Act.  I have to say to the Committee that I have not received a submission yet, and of course I cannot in any way indicate what my decision might be, simply because that would prejudice the case as we go forward.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Q14 </span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Glenda Jackson:</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> Should you not be pushing for that?  There are 22,000 ILF users.  They are in a state of great uncertainty.  Should that not be on the top of your list?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Mike Penning</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">: It is very much on the top of my list to get it right, and that is the important thing.  The submission will be different, based on, obviously, the court ruling and information that has come in subsequently since the decision was made on ILF, but it would be wrong and improper</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">—I am sure you will understand, Madam Chair—if I in any way indicate </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">how </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">I am going to make a decision.  I accept it is a very important decision, but I am also sure that the Committee would accept that we have to make sure that I make the decision in an impartial way, and based on what I see in front of me.  I am not seeing anything yet.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Q15 </span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Glenda Jackson:</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> But you said you are gathering information.  From whence is that information coming?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Mike Penning</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">: I am not gathering information.  Nothing has been submitted.  My officials will continue to gather information, and then I will wait for that 